properties.knowledgeBase: Quinoa, classified as a cereal, holds significant nutritional value. Its rich macronutrient profile includes 376 calories per 100g, which is primarily derived from carbohydrates (57.8g). This complex carbohydrate content provides sustained energy levels and regulates blood sugar. Quinoa is also a notable source of protein (15.4g), comprising all essential amino acids, making it a complete plant-based protein source. Its fat content (8.1g) is predominantly unsaturated, contributing to heart health. The presence of essential vitamins, minerals, and fiber, such as iron, magnesium, and dietary fiber, further enhances quinoa's nutritional status. Its high protein and fiber content promotes satiety, supporting weight management and maintaining blood sugar levels. As a gluten-free grain, quinoa is a suitable option for individuals with celiac disease or gluten sensitivity. Its nutritional composition makes it an excellent choice for a balanced diet, particularly for vegetarians and  s.

properties.knowledgeBase: Soy yogurt, a plant-based alternative to dairy yogurt, is a nutrient-rich food with unique health benefits. It is a rich source of protein, providing essential amino acids for muscle growth and repair. The balanced ratio of protein to carbohydrates and fat makes soy yogurt a satiating food that supports weight management and blood sugar control. Additionally, soy yogurt contains isoflavones, plant compounds with antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties linked to reduced risk of chronic diseases. Regular consumption of soy yogurt as part of a balanced diet may contribute to improved cardiovascular health, reduced menopausal symptoms, and protection against osteoporosis. It is a versatile food item that can be enjoyed plain, in smoothies, or as a topping for cereals and fruit.

properties.knowledgeBase: 100% vegetable margarine is a plant-based substitute for butter with a high caloric content (760 kcal/100g) and a substantial fat content (84g/100g). Despite its low protein (0.6g/100g) and carbohydrate (0.4g/100g) content, margarine plays a specific role in a balanced diet as a source of essential fatty acids. The primary fatty acids present are unsaturated and polyunsaturated fats, which have been associated with a reduced risk of cardiovascular disease. However, it is important to note that margarine often contains trans fats, which have been linked to adverse health effects. Optimal consumption involves limiting the intake of trans fats and using margarine sparingly as a cooking oil or spread. Regular intake of 100% vegetable margarine should be balanced with a diverse and nutrient-rich diet to ensure overall well-being.

properties.knowledgeBase: Canned crab, a nutrient-rich delicacy, boasts an impressive nutritional profile. Its low caloric content (81 kcal per serving) and absence of carbohydrates make it ideal for weight management and blood sugar regulation. Remarkably high in protein (18.1g), crab contributes to muscle growth, satiety, and tissue repair. Its lean nature, with only 0.9g of fat, promotes heart health and reduces the risk of chronic diseases. As a rich source of essential minerals like selenium, zinc, and iron, crab plays a vital role in thyroid function, immunity, and red blood cell production. Furthermore, its abundance of omega-3 fatty acids contributes to cognitive health, reduces inflammation, and supports brain function. Optimal consumption includes moderate portions as part of a balanced diet, while fresh or lightly processed crab is preferred over canned varieties to minimize the impact of preservatives.

They are an excellent source of protein, providing 3.9g per serving, which is essential for building and repairing tissues. Porcini mushrooms are low in calories (31.0 per serving) and fat (0.7g), making them a suitable choice for weight management. Additionally, they contain significant amounts of carbohydrates (1.0g), mainly in the form of dietary fiber, which promotes satiety and supports digestive health. The amino acid composition of Porcini mushrooms is well-balanced, providing a range of essential and non-essential amino acids. Their rich vitamin and mineral content includes high levels of selenium, which plays a vital role in thyroid hormone metabolism and antioxidant defense. It is recommended to consume Porcini mushrooms in moderation as part of a balanced diet, ensuring variety and nutrient adequacy.

properties.knowledgeBase: Red beets, a root vegetable esteemed for their deep crimson hue, boast an impressive nutritional profile. With only 25 calories per serving, they are a low-calorie food rich in essential vitamins and minerals. The high carbohydrate content, primarily in the form of soluble fiber, contributes to satiety and supports digestive health. Additionally, beets are a remarkable source of folate, essential for DNA synthesis and cell growth, and potassium, crucial for maintaining fluid balance and regulating blood pressure. Their unique phytochemical composition, including betalains, provides antioxidant protection, while research indicates that regular beet consumption may enhance athletic performance and protect against cognitive decline. Optimal consumption involves incorporating beets into a balanced diet, prepared through boiling, roasting, or juicing to preserve their nutrient content.

properties.knowledgeBase: Venus rice, belonging to the Oryza sativa species, exhibits a distinct nutritional profile. The inclusion of Venus rice in a balanced diet can contribute to meeting daily energy requirements and support cellular functions. The presence of dietary fiber, vitamins, and minerals in Venus rice further enhances its nutritional value. Optimal consumption involves incorporating Venus rice into meals in moderation as part of a varied and balanced diet. Cooking methods that preserve its nutritional integrity, such as steaming or boiling, are recommended.

properties.knowledgeBase: Kiwi fruit, renowned for its emerald-green flesh and tart flavor, stands out as a nutrient-packed powerhouse. With a mere 48 calories, it boasts 1.2g of protein, 0.6g of fat, and 9.0g of carbohydrates, making it a low-calorie, low-fat source of essential nutrients. As a member of the Carbohydrates macro category, kiwi's dietary fiber aids in digestion and satiety, while its high vitamin C content supports immune function and collagen production. Moreover, it is an excellent source of antioxidants like vitamin E and lutein, which play a crucial role in neutralizing free radicals and protecting cells from damage. Optimal consumption of kiwi can be achieved by incorporating it into a balanced diet as a snack, dessert, or ingredient in smoothies and salads. Its unique blend of nutrients and antioxidants makes kiwi an exceptional fruit that contributes significantly to overall health and well-being.

properties.knowledgeBase: Blueberries are nutrient-dense berries with a high antioxidant capacity. They are composed primarily of carbohydrates (10.1g per 49-calorie serving) and provide moderate amounts of protein (0.9g) and minimal fat (0.2g). Blueberries' nutritional value stems from their high content of vitamins, minerals, and polyphenols. Anthocyanins, the primary polyphenols found in blueberries, have been linked to improved cardiovascular health, reduced inflammation, and enhanced cognitive function. Dietary fiber in blueberries promotes satiety and supports digestive health. Regular consumption of blueberries has been associated with a reduced risk of chronic diseases such as type 2 diabetes, obesity, and some types of cancer. Optimal consumption involves incorporating blueberries into a balanced diet, prioritizing fresh or frozen options over processed forms, and maximizing their intake as part of a nutrient-rich eating pattern.

properties.knowledgeBase: Provolone, classified as a legume, is a highly nutritious cheese rich in protein (28.1g per serving) and fat (28.2g). properties.knowledgeBase: Extra virgin olive oil is a type of oil derived from the fruit of the olive tree, consisting primarily of monounsaturated fats (99.9g per 100g). These fats, particularly oleic acid, have been associated with improved cardiovascular health by reducing LDL (bad) cholesterol and increasing HDL (good) cholesterol, contributing to a reduced risk of heart disease. Despite its high caloric content (899kcal per 100g), it contains no carbohydrates or protein, making it a pure source of healthy fats. The oil is also rich in antioxidants, such as vitamin E and polyphenols, which have anti-inflammatory and disease-fighting properties. Optimal consumption of extra virgin olive oil involves incorporating it into a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains. However, it is important to consume it in moderation due to its high caloric content. Its distinct flavor and aroma enhance culinary preparations, making it a versatile ingredient in dressings, sauces, and various dishes.

These fats, particularly oleic acid, have been associated with improved cardiovascular health by reducing LDL (bad) cholesterol and increasing HDL (good) cholesterol, contributing to a reduced risk of heart disease. Despite its high caloric content (899kcal per 100g), it contains no carbohydrates or protein, making it a pure source of healthy fats. The oil is also rich in antioxidants, such as vitamin E and polyphenols, which have anti-inflammatory and disease-fighting properties. Optimal consumption of extra virgin olive oil involves incorporating it into a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains. However, it is important to consume it in moderation due to its high caloric content. Its distinct flavor and aroma enhance culinary preparations, making it a versatile ingredient in dressings, sauces, and various dishes.
properties.name: Extra Virgin Olive Oil

properties.knowledgeBase: Red snapper, a fish belonging to the Lutjanus genus, is a prime source of protein, contributing 16.7g per 100g serving. Its rich protein content promotes muscle growth and repair, enhances satiety, and supports optimal metabolism. The 3.5g of fat present provides energy and aids in nutrient absorption, while the 0.7g of carbohydrates contribute minimally to overall caloric intake. Red snapper's nutritional profile aligns well with a balanced diet, as it provides essential macro- and micronutrients. Key nutrients include vitamin B12, which is crucial for red blood cell production, and selenium, an antioxidant that protects against cellular damage. Optimal consumption involves incorporating red snapper into a varied diet, emphasizing fresh or minimally processed preparation methods to preserve nutritional integrity and minimize the risk of contaminants. Unique properties of red snapper include its distinct flavor and firm texture, which make it a popular culinary choice.

properties.knowledgeBase: Muesli, a high-carbohydrate cereal, provides 374 calories per serving. Its richness in protein (9.7g) and dietary fiber contributes to satiety and blood sugar regulation. The presence of healthy fats (6.0g) promotes cell health and hormone production. Key nutrients include B vitamins, essential for energy metabolism, and iron, crucial for oxygen transport. Evidence suggests that regular consumption of muesli as part of a balanced diet may reduce the risk of cardiovascular diseases due to its soluble fiber content. Studies also indicate its potential in managing type 2 diabetes by slowing down glucose absorption. For optimal consumption, muesli can be paired with fruits, nuts, and seeds to enhance its nutritional value and provide a variety of vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants.

It is a versatile food item that can be enjoyed plain, in smoothies, or as a topping for cereals and fruit.

properties.knowledgeBase: Brussels sprouts, belonging to the Brassicaceae family, are highly nutritious cruciferous vegetables. Its low caloric content (47 per 100g) belies its impressive nutrient profile. Rich in protein (4.2g), dietary fiber (4.2g), and phytonutrients, brussels sprouts contribute to satiety and support gut health. They are also an abundant source of vitamin C, promoting immune function and collagen synthesis. The presence of glucosinolates, sulfur-containing compounds, has been linked to reduced risk of certain cancers. Brussels sprouts are a versatile food that can be enjoyed raw, cooked, or fermented. Optimal consumption includes 1-2 servings per week as part of a balanced diet, contributing to overall health and well-being.

properties.knowledgeBase: Provolone, classified as a legume, is a highly nutritious cheese rich in protein (28.1g per serving) and fat (28.2g). The optimal preparation of provolone involves slicing or grating it and incorporating it into sandwiches, salads, or pasta dishes for enhanced flavor and nutritional value.

properties.knowledgeBase: Provolone, classified as a legume, is a highly nutritious cheese rich in protein (28.1g per serving) and fat (28.2g). The high protein content supports tissue growth and repair, while the saturated fat content may provide energy and heat insulation. Provolone also contains minimal carbohydrates (2.0g), making it suitable for low-carb diets. Key nutrients in provolone include calcium, essential for bone health, and vitamin A, crucial for vision and immune function. As part of a balanced diet, moderate consumption of provolone can contribute to overall nutritional adequacy. However, individuals with high cholesterol should exercise caution due to its high fat content. The optimal preparation of provolone involves slicing or grating it and incorporating it into sandwiches, salads, or pasta dishes for enhanced flavor and nutritional value.

properties.knowledgeBase: Provolone, classified as a legume, is a highly nutritious cheese rich in protein (28.1g per serving) and fat (28.2g). The high protein content supports tissue growth and repair, while the saturated fat content may provide energy and heat insulation. Provolone also contains minimal carbohydrates (2.0g), making it suitable for low-carb diets. Key nutrients in provolone include calcium, essential for bone health, and vitamin A, crucial for vision and immune function. As part of a balanced diet, moderate consumption of provolone can contribute to overall nutritional adequacy. However, individuals with high cholesterol should exercise caution due to its high fat content. The optimal preparation of provolone involves slicing or grating it and incorporating it into sandwiches, salads, or pasta dishes for enhanced flavor and nutritional value.

properties.knowledgeBase: Litchi, a member of the soapberry family, is a tropical fruit notable for its high nutritional value. It is exceptionally low in fat and calories, with only 72 calories per 100 grams. Its macronutrient profile comprises 1.1 grams of protein, 17.2 grams of carbohydrates, and a negligible amount of fat. Litchi's nutritional composition makes it an ideal choice for weight management and overall health. The presence of dietary fiber in litchi aids digestion, prevents constipation, and promotes satiety. Furthermore, its high vitamin C content (71.5 mg per 100 grams) supports immune function and collagen production, contributing to healthy skin and connective tissues. Litchi is recommended as a part of a balanced diet due to its richness in vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants. Its low glycemic index makes it suitable for individuals with blood sugar concerns. Optimal consumption involves fresh, unprocessed litchi or incorporating it into salads, smoothies, and desserts. However, individuals should consider limiting excessive intake due to its moderately high sugar content.

properties.knowledgeBase: Lupins, members of the legume family, are highly nutritious with an impressive macronutrient profile. properties.knowledgeBase: Soy yogurt, a plant-based alternative to dairy yogurt, is a nutrient-rich food with unique health benefits. It is a rich source of protein, providing essential amino acids for muscle growth and repair. The balanced ratio of protein to carbohydrates and fat makes soy yogurt a satiating food that supports weight management and blood sugar control. Additionally, soy yogurt contains isoflavones, plant compounds with antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties linked to reduced risk of chronic diseases. Regular consumption of soy yogurt as part of a balanced diet may contribute to improved cardiovascular health, reduced menopausal symptoms, and protection against osteoporosis. It is a versatile food item that can be enjoyed plain, in smoothies, or as a topping for cereals and fruit.

properties.knowledgeBase: Extra virgin olive oil is a type of oil derived from the fruit of the olive tree, consisting primarily of monounsaturated fats (99.9g per 100g). These fats, particularly oleic acid, have been associated with improved cardiovascular health by reducing LDL (bad) cholesterol and increasing HDL (good) cholesterol, contributing to a reduced risk of heart disease. Optimal consumption of extra virgin olive oil involves incorporating it into a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains. However, it is important to consume it in moderation due to its high caloric content. Its distinct flavor and aroma enhance culinary preparations, making it a versatile ingredient in dressings, sauces, and various dishes.

However, it is important to note that squid contains elevated levels of cholesterol, and consumption should be moderated to avoid potential adverse effects.

Optimal consumption includes incorporating radishes into a balanced diet, consuming them raw to preserve their nutrient content, and exploring their versatility in salads, stir-fries, and as a garnish.

Its distinct flavor and aroma enhance culinary preparations, making it a versatile ingredient in dressings, sauces, and various dishes.

Boasting 159 calories per serving, tuna is a lean source of protein (21.5g), with a modest fat content (8.1g) and negligible carbohydrates (0.1g). Its high protein content contributes to satiety, muscle maintenance, and tissue repair. Tuna's abundance in omega-3 fatty acids, primarily eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), plays a crucial role in cardiovascular health, reducing inflammation and supporting cognitive function. Additionally, tuna is a rich source of B vitamins, including niacin, vitamin B6, and vitamin B12, which are essential for energy metabolism, nerve function, and red blood cell formation. Optimal consumption involves incorporating tuna into a balanced diet as a primary protein source, aiming for 2-3 servings per week. Steaming or grilling tuna retains its nutritional value while minimizing fat intake.
properties.name: Tuna

The presence of dietary fiber, vitamins, and minerals in Venus rice further enhances its nutritional value. Optimal consumption involves incorporating Venus rice into meals in moderation as part of a varied and balanced diet. Cooking methods that preserve its nutritional integrity, such as steaming or boiling, are recommended.

properties.knowledgeBase: Extra virgin olive oil is a type of oil derived from the fruit of the olive tree, consisting primarily of monounsaturated fats (99.9g per 100g). Its distinct flavor and aroma enhance culinary preparations, making it a versatile ingredient in dressings, sauces, and various dishes.

properties.knowledgeBase: Greek yogurt 0% is a high-protein, low-fat dairy product that plays a significant role in a balanced diet. Its high protein content, at 9.0g per serving, contributes to satiety, promoting fullness and reducing overall calorie intake. The absence of fat makes it a suitable option for individuals seeking to maintain a healthy weight or manage cholesterol levels. Additionally, Greek yogurt contains carbohydrates, primarily in the form of lactose, which provides a source of energy and supports the growth of beneficial gut bacteria. The unique straining process in Greek yogurt production results in a concentrated form of dairy, making it an excellent source of calcium, potassium, and other essential minerals that support bone, muscle, and nerve function. Due to its nutritional value, Greek yogurt 0% is recommended as a lean protein source in various dietary guidelines and can be incorporated into a balanced diet in versatile ways, such as in smoothies, dips, or as a topping for salads or fruit.

Studies also indicate its potential in managing type 2 diabetes by slowing down glucose absorption. For optimal consumption, muesli can be paired with fruits, nuts, and seeds to enhance its nutritional value and provide a variety of vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants.

properties.knowledgeBase: Fresh salmon is a nutrient-rich fish renowned for its exceptional nutritional profile. It is an excellent source of high-quality protein (18.4g per 100g), providing essential amino acids necessary for muscle growth, repair, and hormone production. Salmon is also rich in omega-3 fatty acids (12.0g per 100g), particularly eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), which have been linked to reduced inflammation, improved cardiovascular health, and brain function. The high protein and fat content of salmon promote satiety and provide sustained energy levels. Additionally, salmon is a good source of vitamins (B12, D, and A) and minerals (selenium, iron, and zinc), which are vital for various bodily functions. As part of a balanced diet, salmon consumption of about 2-3 servings per week is recommended to optimize its nutritional benefits while minimizing any potential risks associated with mercury exposure.

properties.knowledgeBase: Radishes (Raphanus sativus) are nutrient-rich vegetables with a low-calorie profile. They provide essential nutrients such as vitamin C, potassium, folate, and fiber. The high vitamin C content supports immune function and antioxidant activity, protecting cells from damage. Potassium aids in maintaining fluid balance and regulating blood pressure. Folate contributes to red blood cell formation and DNA synthesis. Radishes also contain glucosinolates, sulfur-containing compounds that have been linked to anti-inflammatory and anticancer effects. Optimal consumption includes incorporating radishes into a balanced diet, consuming them raw to preserve their nutrient content, and exploring their versatility in salads, stir-fries, and as a garnish.

properties.knowledgeBase: Chicory, a member of the vegetable category, is a nutrient-rich food known for its low caloric content (17kcal/100g) and high fiber content. With 1.4g of protein and only 0.2g of fat, chicory provides a substantial amount of nutrients without significantly contributing to daily caloric intake. Inulin, a type of dietary fiber, promotes satiety, regulates bowel function, and supports gut microbiota health. Its 0.7g of carbohydrates are primarily composed of inulin, which acts as a prebiotic, feeding beneficial bacteria in the digestive tract, leading to a healthy microbiome and potential immune-modulating effects. Chicory's unique properties and nutritional value, including its high fiber content and prebiotic effects, make it a valuable addition to a balanced diet, contributing to both digestive health and overall well-being.

Its caloric value (239 kcal/100g) is lower compared to regular cheese, making it a viable option for calorie-conscious individuals. The protein content (14.7g/100g) supports muscle growth and repair, while the presence of carbohydrates (6.5g/100g) provides energy. Key nutrients include calcium, essential for bone health, and riboflavin, which contributes to energy metabolism and cellular function. Moderate consumption of low-fat cheese as part of a balanced diet may promote satiety, support weight management, and contribute to overall well-being.

properties.knowledgeBase: Lupins, members of the legume family, are highly nutritious with an impressive macronutrient profile. They are a rich source of protein (16.4g/100g), contributing to muscle growth and providing satiety. Lupins also boast a low-fat content (2.4g/100g) and ample carbohydrates (7.1g/100g), offering sustained energy. Scientific evidence suggests that lupins provide several health benefits. Their fiber content promotes digestive health, while their iron content combats anemia. Additionally, the high protein content fosters muscle growth and maintenance, making lupins a valuable addition to a balanced diet. Optimal consumption involves incorporating cooked or sprouted lupins into salads, soups, and stews. Their unique bitter alkaloid content, which can be reduced through proper soaking and preparation, distinguishes them from other legumes and adds a distinctive flavor to culinary creations.

properties.knowledgeBase: Peas, legumes rich in carbohydrates (6.5g) and protein (5.5g), provide 64 calories per 100g serving. Their low fat content (0.6g) makes them a heart-healthy choice. Peas are excellent sources of dietary fiber, essential for digestive health and blood sugar regulation. They also contain significant amounts of vitamins A, C, and K, as well as folate, supporting immune function, antioxidant defenses, and cell growth. Optimal consumption involves incorporating peas into a balanced diet as part of recommended daily legume intake. Steaming or boiling peas preserves their nutrients while enhancing their flavor and texture. Notably, peas contain unique compounds like lutein and zeaxanthin, carotenoids vital for eye health, providing further evidence of their nutritional significance.

properties.knowledgeBase: Cabbage buckwheat, a nutrient-rich vegetable, is a low-calorie source of essential vitamins and minerals. With just 29 calories per serving, it provides a substantial amount of protein (2 grams), dietary fiber, and carbohydrates. The fiber aids in digestion and satiety, while the protein supports muscle growth and repair. Cabbage buckwheat contains antioxidants that combat cellular damage and reduce inflammation. It is an excellent source of vitamin C, which is crucial for immune function and collagen production. Additionally, it provides antioxidants and flavonoids that protect against oxidative stress and reduce the risk of chronic diseases. Optimal consumption involves incorporating cabbage buckwheat into a balanced diet, incorporating it into salads, stir-fries, or as a side dish. It should be cooked lightly to preserve its nutrient value.

properties.knowledgeBase: Chestnuts stand out as a nutrient-rich dried fruit. With 174 calories per serving, they offer 2.9g of protein, 1.7g of healthy fats, and 36.7g of carbohydrates, primarily in the form of fiber and resistant starch. These complex carbohydrates support satiety, stabilize blood sugar levels, and promote a balanced microbiome. The presence of manganese and potassium in chestnuts enhances bone health, nerve function, and electrolyte balance. Additionally, chestnuts are a source of antioxidants, such as vitamin C and ellagic acid, which protect against oxidative stress and chronic diseases. Optimal consumption involves incorporating chestnuts into a balanced diet as a snack or side dish, replacing refined grains or sugary treats. Their unique nutty flavor and nutritional profile make them a valuable addition to a healthy and varied diet.

properties.knowledgeBase: Soy yogurt, a plant-based alternative to dairy yogurt, is a nutrient-rich food with unique health benefits. It is a rich source of protein, providing essential amino acids for muscle growth and repair. The balanced ratio of protein to carbohydrates and fat makes soy yogurt a satiating food that supports weight management and blood sugar control. Additionally, soy yogurt contains isoflavones, plant compounds with antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties linked to reduced risk of chronic diseases. Regular consumption of soy yogurt as part of a balanced diet may contribute to improved cardiovascular health, reduced menopausal symptoms, and protection against osteoporosis. It is a versatile food item that can be enjoyed plain, in smoothies, or as a topping for cereals and fruit.

Dumbbell Alternate Bicep Curl
properties.description: Stand (torso upright) with a dumbbell in each hand held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso and the palms of your hand should be facing your thighs.. While holding the upper arm stationary, curl the right weight as you rotate the palm of the hands until they are facing forward. At this point continue contracting the biceps as you breathe out until your biceps is fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder level. Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the biceps. Tip: Only the forearms should move.. Slowly begin to bring the dumbbell back to the starting position as your breathe in. Tip: Remember to twist the palms back to the starting position (facing your thighs) as you come down.. Repeat the movement with the left hand. This equals one repetition.. Continue alternating in this manner for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Dumbbell Alternate Bicep Curl
properties.description: Stand (torso upright) with a dumbbell in each hand held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso and the palms of your hand should be facing your thighs.. Tip: Remember to twist the palms back to the starting position (facing your thighs) as you come down.. Repeat the movement with the left hand. This equals one repetition.. properties.name: One Arm Dumbbell Preacher Curl
properties.description: Grab a dumbbell with the right arm and place the upper arm on top of the preacher bench or the incline bench. The dumbbell should be held at shoulder length. This will be your starting position.. As you breathe in, slowly lower the dumbbell until your upper arm is extended and the biceps is fully stretched.. As you exhale, use the biceps to curl the weight up until your biceps is fully contracted and the dumbbell is at shoulder height. Again, remember that to ensure full contraction you need to bring that small finger higher than the thumb.. Squeeze the biceps hard for a second at the contracted position and repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.. Switch arms and repeat the movement.

properties.name: Parallel Bar Dip
properties.description: Stand between a set of parallel bars. Place a hand on each bar, and then take a small jump to help you get into the starting position with your arms locked out.. Begin by flexing the elbow, lowering your body until your arms break 90 degrees. Avoid swinging, and maintain good posture throughout the descent.. Reverse the motion by extending the elbow, pushing yourself back up into the starting position.. Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

properties.name: Parallel Bar Dip
properties.description: Stand between a set of parallel bars. Place a hand on each bar, and then take a small jump to help you get into the starting position with your arms locked out.. Begin by flexing the elbow, lowering your body until your arms break 90 degrees. Avoid swinging, and maintain good posture throughout the descent.. Reverse the motion by extending the elbow, pushing yourself back up into the starting position.. Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

properties.name: Standing Overhead Barbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: To begin, stand up holding a barbell or e-z bar using a pronated grip (palms facing forward) with your hands closer than shoulder width apart from each other. Your feet should be about shoulder width apart.. Now elevate the barbell above your head until your arms are fully extended. Keep your elbows in. This will be your starting position.. Keeping your upper arms close to your head and elbows in, perpendicular to the floor, lower the resistance in a semicircular motion behind your head until your forearms touch your biceps. Tip: The upper arms should remain stationary and only the forearms should move. Breathe in as you perform this step.. Go back to the starting position by using the triceps to raise the barbell. Breathe out as you perform this step.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Standing Overhead Barbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: To begin, stand up holding a barbell or e-z bar using a pronated grip (palms facing forward) with your hands closer than shoulder width apart from each other. Your feet should be about shoulder width apart.. Now elevate the barbell above your head until your arms are fully extended. Keep your elbows in. This will be your starting position.. Keeping your upper arms close to your head and elbows in, perpendicular to the floor, lower the resistance in a semicircular motion behind your head until your forearms touch your biceps. Tip: The upper arms should remain stationary and only the forearms should move. Breathe in as you perform this step.. Go back to the starting position by using the triceps to raise the barbell. Breathe out as you perform this step.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Chin-Up
properties.description: Grab the pull-up bar with the palms facing your torso and a grip closer than the shoulder width.. As you have both arms extended in front of you holding the bar at the chosen grip width, keep your torso as straight as possible while creating a curvature on your lower back and sticking your chest out. This is your starting position. Tip: Keeping the torso as straight as possible maximizes biceps stimulation while minimizing back involvement.. As you breathe out, pull your torso up until your head is around the level of the pull-up bar. Concentrate on using the biceps muscles in order to perform the movement. Keep the elbows close to your body. Tip: The upper torso should remain stationary as it moves through space and only the arms should move. The forearms should do no other work other than hold the bar.. After a second of squeezing the biceps in the contracted position, slowly lower your torso back to the starting position; when your arms are fully extended. Breathe in as you perform this portion of the movement.. Repeat this motion for the prescribed amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Landmine 180's
properties.description: Position a bar into a landmine or securely anchor it in a corner. Load the bar to an appropriate weight.. Raise the bar from the floor, taking it to shoulder height with both hands with your arms extended in front of you. Adopt a wide stance. This will be your starting position.. Perform the movement by rotating the trunk and hips as you swing the weight all the way down to one side. Keep your arms extended throughout the exercise.. Reverse the motion to swing the weight all the way to the opposite side.. Continue alternating the movement until the set is complete.

properties.name: Seated Flat Bench Leg Pull-In
properties.description: Sit on a bench with the legs stretched out in front of you slightly below parallel and your arms holding on to the sides of the bench. Your torso should be leaning backwards around a 45-degree angle from the bench. This will be your starting position.. Bring the knees in toward you as you move your torso closer to them at the same time. Breathe out as you perform this movement.. After a second pause, go back to the starting position as you inhale.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Weighted Pull Ups
properties.description: Attach a weight to a dip belt and secure it around your waist. Grab the pull-up bar with the palms of your hands facing forward. For a medium grip, your hands should be spaced at shoulder width. Both arms should be extended in front of you holding the bar at the chosen grip.. You'll want to bring your torso back about 30 degrees while creating a curvature in your lower back and sticking your chest out. This will be your starting position.. Now, exhale and pull your torso up until your head is above your hands. Concentrate on squeezing yourshoulder blades back and down as you reach the top contracted position.. After a brief moment at the top contracted position, inhale and slowly lower your torso back to the starting position with your arms extended and your lats fully stretched.

properties.name: Dip Machine
properties.description: Sit securely in a dip machine, select the weight and firmly grasp the handles.. Now keep your elbows in at your sides in order to place emphasis on the triceps. The elbows should be bent at a 90 degree angle.. As you contract the triceps, extend your arms downwards as you exhale. Tip: At the bottom of the movement, focus on keeping a little bend in your arms to keep tension on the triceps muscle.. Now slowly let your arms come back up to the starting position as you inhale.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Hack Squat
properties.description: Place the back of your torso against the back pad of the machine and hook your shoulders under the shoulder pads provided.. Position your legs in the platform using a shoulder width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Tip: Keep your head up at all times and also maintain the back on the pad at all times.. Place your arms on the side handles of the machine and disengage the safety bars (which on most designs is done by moving the side handles from a facing front position to a diagonal position).. Now straighten your legs without locking the knees. This will be your starting position. (Note: For the purposes of this discussion we will use the medium stance described above which targets overall development; however you can choose any of the three stances described in the foot positioning section).. Begin to slowly lower the unit by bending the knees as you maintain a straight posture with the head up (back on the pad at all times). Continue down until the angle between the upper leg and the calves becomes slightly less than 90-degrees (which is the point in which the upper legs are below parallel to the floor). Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that is perpendicular to the front. If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.. Begin to raise the unit as you exhale by pushing the floor with mainly with the heel of your foot as you straighten the legs again and go back to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Incline Barbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: Hold a barbell with an overhand grip (palms down) that is a little closer together than shoulder width.. Lie back on an incline bench set at any angle between 45-75-degrees.. Bring the bar overhead with your arms extended and elbows in. The arms should be in line with the torso above the head. This will be your starting position.. Now lower the bar in a semicircular motion behind your head until your forearms touch your biceps. Inhale as you perform this movement. Tip: Keep your upper arms stationary and close to your head at all times. Only the forearms should move.. Return to the starting position as you breathe out and you contract the triceps. Hold the contraction for a second.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Incline Barbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: Hold a barbell with an overhand grip (palms down) that is a little closer together than shoulder width.. Lie back on an incline bench set at any angle between 45-75-degrees.. Bring the bar overhead with your arms extended and elbows in. The arms should be in line with the torso above the head. This will be your starting position.. Now lower the bar in a semicircular motion behind your head until your forearms touch your biceps. Inhale as you perform this movement. Tip: Keep your upper arms stationary and close to your head at all times. Only the forearms should move.. Return to the starting position as you breathe out and you contract the triceps. Hold the contraction for a second.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Smith Machine Reverse Calf Raises
properties.description: Adjust the barbell on the smith machine to fit your height and align a raised platform right under the bar.. Stand on the platform with the heels of your feet secured on top of it with the balls of your feet extending off it. Position your toes facing forward with a shoulder width stance.. Now, place your shoulders under the barbell while maintaining the foot positioning described and push the barbell up by extending your hips and knees until your torso is standing erect. The knees should be kept with a slight bend; never locked. This will be your starting position. Tip: The barbell on your back is only for balance purposes.. Raise the balls of your feet as you breathe out by extending your toes as high as possible and flexing your calf. Ensure that the knee is kept stationary at all times. There should be no bending at any time. Hold the contracted position for a second before you start to go back down.. Slowly go back down to the starting position as you breathe in by lowering the balls of your feet and toes.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Smith Machine Reverse Calf Raises
properties.description: Adjust the barbell on the smith machine to fit your height and align a raised platform right under the bar.. Stand on the platform with the heels of your feet secured on top of it with the balls of your feet extending off it. Position your toes facing forward with a shoulder width stance.. Now, place your shoulders under the barbell while maintaining the foot positioning described and push the barbell up by extending your hips and knees until your torso is standing erect. The knees should be kept with a slight bend; never locked. This will be your starting position. Tip: The barbell on your back is only for balance purposes.. Raise the balls of your feet as you breathe out by extending your toes as high as possible and flexing your calf. Ensure that the knee is kept stationary at all times. There should be no bending at any time. Hold the contracted position for a second before you start to go back down.. Slowly go back down to the starting position as you breathe in by lowering the balls of your feet and toes.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Barbell Full Squat
properties.description: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack just above shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.. Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.. Step away from the rack and position your legs using a shoulder-width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Keep your head up at all times and maintain a straight back. This will be your starting position.. Begin to slowly lower the bar by bending the knees and sitting back with your hips as you maintain a straight posture with the head up. Continue down until your hamstrings are on your calves. Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement.. Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the heel or middle of your foot as you straighten the legs and extend the hips to go back to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Barbell Full Squat
properties.description: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack just above shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.. Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.. Step away from the rack and position your legs using a shoulder-width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Keep your head up at all times and maintain a straight back. This will be your starting position.. Begin to slowly lower the bar by bending the knees and sitting back with your hips as you maintain a straight posture with the head up. Continue down until your hamstrings are on your calves. Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement.. Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the heel or middle of your foot as you straighten the legs and extend the hips to go back to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Squats - With Bands
properties.description: To start out, make sure that the exercise band is at an even split between both the left and right side of the body. To do this, use your hands to grab both sides of the band and place both feet in the middle of the band. Your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other.. When holding the bands, they should be the same height on each side. You should be using a pronated grip (palms facing forward) and have the handles of the bands next to your face for this exercise. This is the starting position.. Slowly start to bend the knees and lower the legs so that your thighs are parallel to the floor while exhaling.. Use the heel of your feet to push your body up to the starting position as you exhale.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Squats - With Bands
properties.description: To start out, make sure that the exercise band is at an even split between both the left and right side of the body. To do this, use your hands to grab both sides of the band and place both feet in the middle of the band. Your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other.. When holding the bands, they should be the same height on each side. You should be using a pronated grip (palms facing forward) and have the handles of the bands next to your face for this exercise. This is the starting position.. Slowly start to bend the knees and lower the legs so that your thighs are parallel to the floor while exhaling.. Use the heel of your feet to push your body up to the starting position as you exhale.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Band Assisted Pull-Up
properties.description: Choke the band around the center of the pullup bar. You can use different bands to provide varying levels of assistance.. Pull the end of the band down, and place one bent knee into the loop, ensuring it won't slip out. Take a medium to wide grip on the bar. This will be your starting position.. Pull yourself upward by contracting the lats as you flex the elbow. The elbow should be driven to your side. Pull to the front, attempting to get your chin over the bar. Avoid swinging or jerking movements.. After a brief pause, return to the starting position.

properties.name: Board Press
properties.description: Begin by lying on the bench, getting your head beyond the bar if possible. One to five boards, made out of 2x6's, can be screwed together and held in place by a training partner, bands, or just tucked under your shirt.. Tuck your feet underneath you and arch your back. Using the bar to help support your weight, lift your shoulder off the bench and retract them, squeezing the shoulder blades together. Use your feet to drive your traps into the bench. Maintain this tight body position throughout the movement.. You can take a standard bench grip, or shoulder width to focus on the triceps. Pull the bar out of the rack without protracting your shoulders. The bar, wrist, and elbow should stay in line at all times. Focus on squeezing the bar and trying to pull it apart.. Lower the bar to the boards, and then drive the bar up with as much force as possible. The elbows should be tucked in until lockout.

Using the bar to help support your weight, lift your shoulder off the bench and retract them, squeezing the shoulder blades together. Use your feet to drive your traps into the bench. Maintain this tight body position throughout the movement.. You can take a standard bench grip, or shoulder width to focus on the triceps. Pull the bar out of the rack without protracting your shoulders. The bar, wrist, and elbow should stay in line at all times. Focus on squeezing the bar and trying to pull it apart.. Lower the bar to the boards, and then drive the bar up with as much force as possible. The elbows should be tucked in until lockout.

properties.name: Latissimus Dorsi-SMR
properties.description: While lying on the floor, place a foam roll under your back and to one side, just behind your arm pit. This will be your starting position.. Keep the arm of the side being stretched behind and to the side of you as you shift your weight onto your lats, keeping your upper body off of the ground. Hold for 10-30 seconds, and switch sides.

properties.name: Latissimus Dorsi-SMR
properties.description: While lying on the floor, place a foam roll under your back and to one side, just behind your arm pit. This will be your starting position.. Keep the arm of the side being stretched behind and to the side of you as you shift your weight onto your lats, keeping your upper body off of the ground. Hold for 10-30 seconds, and switch sides.

properties.name: Tate Press
properties.description: Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell in each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.. By using your thighs to help you get the dumbbells up, clean the dumbbells one arm at a time so that you can hold them in front of you at shoulder width. Note: when holding the dumbbells in front of you, make sure your arms are wider than shoulder width apart from each other using a pronated (palms forward) grip. Allow your elbows to point out. This is your starting position.. Keeping the upper arms stationary, slowly move the dumbbells in and down in a semi circular motion until they touch the upper chest while inhaling. Keep full control of the dumbbells at all times and do not move the upper arms nor rest the dumbbells on the chest.. As you breathe out, move the dumbbells up using your triceps and the same semi-circular motion but in reverse. Attempt to keep the dumbbells together as they move up. Lock your arms in the contracted position, hold for a second and then start coming down again slowly again. Tip: It should take at least twice as long to go down than to come up.. Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions of your training program.

Note: when holding the dumbbells in front of you, make sure your arms are wider than shoulder width apart from each other using a pronated (palms forward) grip. Allow your elbows to point out. This is your starting position.. Keeping the upper arms stationary, slowly move the dumbbells in and down in a semi circular motion until they touch the upper chest while inhaling. Keep full control of the dumbbells at all times and do not move the upper arms nor rest the dumbbells on the chest.. properties.name: Floor Glute-Ham Raise
properties.description: You can use a partner for this exercise or brace your feet under something stable.. Begin on your knees with your upper legs and torso upright. If using a partner, they will firmly hold your feet to keep you in position. This will be your starting position.. Lower yourself by extending at the knee, taking care to NOT flex the hips as you go forward.. Place your hands in front of you as you reach the floor. This movement is very difficult and you may be unable to do it unaided. Use your arms to lightly push off the floor to aid your return to the starting position.

properties.description: You can use a partner for this exercise or brace your feet under something stable.. Begin on your knees with your upper legs and torso upright. properties.name: On Your Side Quad Stretch
properties.description: Start off by lying on your right side, with your right knee bent at a 90-degree angle resting on the floor in front of you (this stabilizes the torso).. Bend your left knee behind you and hold your left foot with your left hand. To stretch your hip flexor, press your left hip forward as you push your left foot back into your hand. Switch sides.

properties.name: On Your Side Quad Stretch
properties.description: Start off by lying on your right side, with your right knee bent at a 90-degree angle resting on the floor in front of you (this stabilizes the torso).. Bend your left knee behind you and hold your left foot with your left hand. To stretch your hip flexor, press your left hip forward as you push your left foot back into your hand. Switch sides.

properties.name: Knee Tuck Jump
properties.description: Begin in a comfortable standing position with your knees slightly bent. Hold your hands in front of you, palms down with your fingertips together at chest height. This will be your starting position.. Rapidly dip down into a quarter squat and immediately explode upward. Drive the knees towards the chest, attempting to touch them to the palms of the hands.. Jump as high as you can, raising your knees up, and then ensure a good land be re-extending your legs, absorbing impact through be allowing the knees to rebend.

properties.name: Knee Tuck Jump
properties.description: Begin in a comfortable standing position with your knees slightly bent. Hold your hands in front of you, palms down with your fingertips together at chest height. This will be your starting position.. Rapidly dip down into a quarter squat and immediately explode upward. Drive the knees towards the chest, attempting to touch them to the palms of the hands.. properties.name: Power Snatch
properties.description: Begin with a loaded barbell on the floor. The bar should be close to or touching the shins, and a wide grip should be taken on the bar. The feet should be directly below the hips, with the feet turned out as needed. Lower the hips, with the chest up and the head looking forward. The shoulders should be just in front of the bar. This will be the starting position.. Begin the first pull by driving through the front of the heels, raising the bar from the ground. The back angle should stay the same until the bar passes the knees.. Transition into the second pull by extending through the hips knees and ankles, driving the bar up as quickly as possible. The bar should be close to the body. At peak extension, shrug the shoulders and allow the elbows to flex to the side.. As you move your feet into the receiving position, a slightly wider position, pull yourself below the bar as you elevate the bar overhead. The bar should be received in a partial squat. Continue raising the bar to the overhead position, receiving the bar locked out overhead.. Return to a standing position with the weight over head.

properties.name: Power Snatch
properties.description: Begin with a loaded barbell on the floor. The bar should be close to or touching the shins, and a wide grip should be taken on the bar. The feet should be directly below the hips, with the feet turned out as needed. Lower the hips, with the chest up and the head looking forward. The shoulders should be just in front of the bar. This will be the starting position.. Begin the first pull by driving through the front of the heels, raising the bar from the ground. The back angle should stay the same until the bar passes the knees.. Transition into the second pull by extending through the hips knees and ankles, driving the bar up as quickly as possible. The bar should be close to the body. At peak extension, shrug the shoulders and allow the elbows to flex to the side.. As you move your feet into the receiving position, a slightly wider position, pull yourself below the bar as you elevate the bar overhead. The bar should be received in a partial squat. Continue raising the bar to the overhead position, receiving the bar locked out overhead.. Return to a standing position with the weight over head.

properties.name: Reverse Plate Curls
properties.description: Start by standing straight with a weighted plate held by both hands and arms fully extended. Use a pronated grip (palms facing down) and make sure your fingers grab the rough side of the plate while your thumb grabs the smooth side. Note: For the best results, grab the weighted plate at an 11:00 and 1:00 o'clock position.. Your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other and the weighted plate should be near the groin area. This is the starting position.. Slowly lift the plate up while keeping the elbows in and the upper arms stationary until your biceps and forearms touch while exhaling. The plate should be evenly aligned with your torso at this point.. Feel the contraction for a second and begin to lower the weight back down to the starting position while inhaling. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Reverse Plate Curls
properties.description: Start by standing straight with a weighted plate held by both hands and arms fully extended. Use a pronated grip (palms facing down) and make sure your fingers grab the rough side of the plate while your thumb grabs the smooth side. Note: For the best results, grab the weighted plate at an 11:00 and 1:00 o'clock position.. Your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other and the weighted plate should be near the groin area. This is the starting position.. Slowly lift the plate up while keeping the elbows in and the upper arms stationary until your biceps and forearms touch while exhaling. The plate should be evenly aligned with your torso at this point.. Feel the contraction for a second and begin to lower the weight back down to the starting position while inhaling. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Zottman Preacher Curl
properties.description: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and place your upper arms on top of the preacher bench or the incline bench. The dumbbells should be held at shoulder height and the elbows should be flexed. Hold the dumbbells with the palms of your hands facing down. This will be your starting position.. As you breathe in, slowly lower the dumbbells keeping the palms down until your upper arm is extended and your biceps are fully stretched.. Now rotate your wrists once you are at the bottom of the movement so that the palms of the hands are facing up.. As you exhale, use your biceps to curl the weights up until they are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder height. Again, remember that to ensure full contraction you need to bring that small finger higher than the thumb.. Squeeze the biceps hard for a second at the contracted position and rotate your wrists so that the palms are facing down again.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Zottman Preacher Curl
properties.description: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and place your upper arms on top of the preacher bench or the incline bench. The dumbbells should be held at shoulder height and the elbows should be flexed. Hold the dumbbells with the palms of your hands facing down. This will be your starting position.. As you breathe in, slowly lower the dumbbells keeping the palms down until your upper arm is extended and your biceps are fully stretched.. Now rotate your wrists once you are at the bottom of the movement so that the palms of the hands are facing up.. As you exhale, use your biceps to curl the weights up until they are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder height. Again, remember that to ensure full contraction you need to bring that small finger higher than the thumb.. Squeeze the biceps hard for a second at the contracted position and rotate your wrists so that the palms are facing down again.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Cable Russian Twists
properties.description: Connect a standard handle attachment, and position the cable to a middle pulley position.. Lie on a stability ball perpendicular to the cable and grab the handle with one hand. You should be approximately arm's length away from the pulley, with the tension of the weight on the cable.. Grab the handle with both hands and fully extend your arms above your chest. You hands should be directly in-line with the pulley. If not, adjust the pulley up or down until they are.. Keep your hips elevated and abs engaged. Rotate your torso away from the pulley for a full-quarter rotation. Your body should be flat from head to knees.. Pause for a moment and in a slow and controlled manner reset to the starting position. You should still have side tension on the cable in the resting position.. Repeat the same movement to failure.. Then, reposition and repeat the same series of movements on the opposite side.

properties.name: Cable Russian Twists
properties.description: Connect a standard handle attachment, and position the cable to a middle pulley position.. Lie on a stability ball perpendicular to the cable and grab the handle with one hand. You should be approximately arm's length away from the pulley, with the tension of the weight on the cable.. Grab the handle with both hands and fully extend your arms above your chest. You hands should be directly in-line with the pulley. If not, adjust the pulley up or down until they are.. Keep your hips elevated and abs engaged. Rotate your torso away from the pulley for a full-quarter rotation. Your body should be flat from head to knees.. Pause for a moment and in a slow and controlled manner reset to the starting position. You should still have side tension on the cable in the resting position.. Repeat the same movement to failure.. Then, reposition and repeat the same series of movements on the opposite side.

properties.name: Dumbbell Side Bend
properties.description: Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell on the left hand (palms facing the torso) as you have the right hand holding your waist. Your feet should be placed at shoulder width. This will be your starting position.. While keeping your back straight and your head up, bend only at the waist to the right as far as possible. Breathe in as you bend to the side. Then hold for a second and come back up to the starting position as you exhale. Tip: Keep the rest of the body stationary.. Now repeat the movement but bending to the left instead. Hold for a second and come back to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions and then change hands.

properties.name: Dumbbell Side Bend
properties.description: Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell on the left hand (palms facing the torso) as you have the right hand holding your waist. Your feet should be placed at shoulder width. This will be your starting position.. While keeping your back straight and your head up, bend only at the waist to the right as far as possible. Breathe in as you bend to the side. Then hold for a second and come back up to the starting position as you exhale. Tip: Keep the rest of the body stationary.. Now repeat the movement but bending to the left instead. Hold for a second and come back to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions and then change hands.

properties.name: Seated Bent-Over One-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: Sit down at the end of a flat bench with a dumbbell in one arm using a neutral grip (palms of the hand facing you).. Bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward, by bending at the waist, while keeping the back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Make sure that you keep the head up.. The upper arm with the dumbbell should be close to the torso and aligned with it (lifted up until it is parallel to the floor while the forearms are pointing towards the floor as the hands hold the weights). Tip: There should be a 90-degree angle between the forearms and the upper arm. This is your starting position.. Keeping the upper arm stationary, use the triceps to lift the weight as you exhale until the forearm is parallel to the floor and the whole arm is extended. Like many other arm exercises, only the forearm moves.. After a second contraction at the top, slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position as you inhale.. Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.. Switch arms and repeat the exercise.

properties.name: Seated Bent-Over One-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: Sit down at the end of a flat bench with a dumbbell in one arm using a neutral grip (palms of the hand facing you).. Bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward, by bending at the waist, while keeping the back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Make sure that you keep the head up.. The upper arm with the dumbbell should be close to the torso and aligned with it (lifted up until it is parallel to the floor while the forearms are pointing towards the floor as the hands hold the weights). Tip: There should be a 90-degree angle between the forearms and the upper arm. This is your starting position.. Keeping the upper arm stationary, use the triceps to lift the weight as you exhale until the forearm is parallel to the floor and the whole arm is extended. Like many other arm exercises, only the forearm moves.. After a second contraction at the top, slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position as you inhale.. Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.. Switch arms and repeat the exercise.

properties.name: Triceps Pushdown - Rope Attachment
properties.description: Attach a rope attachment to a high pulley and grab with a neutral grip (palms facing each other).. Standing upright with the torso straight and a very small inclination forward, bring the upper arms close to your body and perpendicular to the floor. The forearms should be pointing up towards the pulley as they hold the rope with the palms facing each other. This is your starting position.. Using the triceps, bring the rope down as you bring each side of the rope to the side of your thighs. At the end of the movement the arms are fully extended and perpendicular to the floor. The upper arms should always remain stationary next to your torso and only the forearms should move. Exhale as you perform this movement.. After holding for a second, at the contracted position, bring the rope slowly up to the starting point. Breathe in as you perform this step.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Triceps Pushdown - Rope Attachment
properties.description: Attach a rope attachment to a high pulley and grab with a neutral grip (palms facing each other).. Standing upright with the torso straight and a very small inclination forward, bring the upper arms close to your body and perpendicular to the floor. The forearms should be pointing up towards the pulley as they hold the rope with the palms facing each other. This is your starting position.. Using the triceps, bring the rope down as you bring each side of the rope to the side of your thighs. At the end of the movement the arms are fully extended and perpendicular to the floor. The upper arms should always remain stationary next to your torso and only the forearms should move. Exhale as you perform this movement.. After holding for a second, at the contracted position, bring the rope slowly up to the starting point. Breathe in as you perform this step.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Concentration Curls
properties.description: Sit down on a flat bench with one dumbbell in front of you between your legs. Your legs should be spread with your knees bent and feet on the floor.. Use your right arm to pick the dumbbell up. Place the back of your right upper arm on the top of your inner right thigh. Rotate the palm of your hand until it is facing forward away from your thigh. Tip: Your arm should be extended and the dumbbell should be above the floor. This will be your starting position.. While holding the upper arm stationary, curl the weights forward while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Only the forearms should move. Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder level. Tip: At the top of the movement make sure that the little finger of your arm is higher than your thumb. This guarantees a good contraction. Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the biceps.. Slowly begin to bring the dumbbells back to starting position as your breathe in. Caution: Avoid swinging motions at any time.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions. Then repeat the movement with the left arm.

properties.name: Concentration Curls
properties.description: Sit down on a flat bench with one dumbbell in front of you between your legs. Your legs should be spread with your knees bent and feet on the floor.. Use your right arm to pick the dumbbell up. Place the back of your right upper arm on the top of your inner right thigh. Rotate the palm of your hand until it is facing forward away from your thigh. Tip: Your arm should be extended and the dumbbell should be above the floor. This will be your starting position.. While holding the upper arm stationary, curl the weights forward while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Only the forearms should move. Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder level. Tip: At the top of the movement make sure that the little finger of your arm is higher than your thumb. This guarantees a good contraction. Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the biceps.. Slowly begin to bring the dumbbells back to starting position as your breathe in. Caution: Avoid swinging motions at any time.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions. Then repeat the movement with the left arm.

properties.name: Hip Flexion with Band
properties.description: Secure one end of the band to the lower portion of a post and attach the other to one ankle.. Face away from the attachment point of the band.. Keeping your head and your chest up, raise your knee up to 90 degrees and pause.. Return the leg to the starting position.

properties.name: Hip Flexion with Band
properties.description: Secure one end of the band to the lower portion of a post and attach the other to one ankle.. Face away from the attachment point of the band.. Keeping your head and your chest up, raise your knee up to 90 degrees and pause.. Return the leg to the starting position.

properties.name: Reverse Cable Curl
properties.description: Stand up with your torso upright while holding a bar attachment that is attached to a low pulley using a pronated (palms down) and shoulder width grip. Make sure also that you keep the elbows close to the torso. This will be your starting position.. While holding the upper arms stationary, curl the weights while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Only the forearms should move. Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the bar is at shoulder level. Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the muscle.. Slowly begin to bring the bar back to starting position as your breathe in.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Reverse Cable Curl
properties.description: Stand up with your torso upright while holding a bar attachment that is attached to a low pulley using a pronated (palms down) and shoulder width grip. Make sure also that you keep the elbows close to the torso. This will be your starting position.. While holding the upper arms stationary, curl the weights while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Only the forearms should move. Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the bar is at shoulder level. Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the muscle.. Slowly begin to bring the bar back to starting position as your breathe in.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Single Leg Butt Kick
properties.description: Begin by standing on one leg, with the bent knee raised. This will be your start position.. Using a countermovement jump, take off upward by extending the hip, knee, and ankle of the grounded leg.. Immediately flex the knee and attempt to touch your butt with the heel of your jumping leg.. Return the leg to a partially bent position underneath the hips and land. Your opposite leg should stay in relatively the same position throughout the drill.

properties.name: Single Leg Butt Kick
properties.description: Begin by standing on one leg, with the bent knee raised. This will be your start position.. Using a countermovement jump, take off upward by extending the hip, knee, and ankle of the grounded leg.. Immediately flex the knee and attempt to touch your butt with the heel of your jumping leg.. Return the leg to a partially bent position underneath the hips and land. Your opposite leg should stay in relatively the same position throughout the drill.

properties.name: Incline Barbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: Hold a barbell with an overhand grip (palms down) that is a little closer together than shoulder width.. Lie back on an incline bench set at any angle between 45-75-degrees.. Bring the bar overhead with your arms extended and elbows in. The arms should be in line with the torso above the head. This will be your starting position.. Now lower the bar in a semicircular motion behind your head until your forearms touch your biceps. Inhale as you perform this movement. Tip: Keep your upper arms stationary and close to your head at all times. Only the forearms should move.. Return to the starting position as you breathe out and you contract the triceps. Hold the contraction for a second.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Incline Barbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: Hold a barbell with an overhand grip (palms down) that is a little closer together than shoulder width.. Lie back on an incline bench set at any angle between 45-75-degrees.. Bring the bar overhead with your arms extended and elbows in. The arms should be in line with the torso above the head. This will be your starting position.. Now lower the bar in a semicircular motion behind your head until your forearms touch your biceps. Inhale as you perform this movement. Tip: Keep your upper arms stationary and close to your head at all times. Only the forearms should move.. Return to the starting position as you breathe out and you contract the triceps. Hold the contraction for a second.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Standing Bent-Over Two-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: With a dumbbell in each hand and the palms facing your torso, bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward, by bending at the waist, while keeping the back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Make sure that you keep the head up. The upper arms should be close to the torso and parallel to the floor while the forearms are pointing towards the floor as the hands hold the weights. Tip: There should be a 90-degree angle between the forearms and the upper arm. This is your starting position.. Keeping the upper arms stationary, use the triceps to lift the weights as you exhale until the forearms are parallel to the floor and the whole arms are extended. Like many other arm exercises, only the forearm moves.. After a second contraction at the top, slowly lower the dumbbells back to their starting position as you inhale.. Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Standing Bent-Over Two-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension
properties.description: With a dumbbell in each hand and the palms facing your torso, bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward, by bending at the waist, while keeping the back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Make sure that you keep the head up. The upper arms should be close to the torso and parallel to the floor while the forearms are pointing towards the floor as the hands hold the weights. Tip: There should be a 90-degree angle between the forearms and the upper arm. This is your starting position.. Keeping the upper arms stationary, use the triceps to lift the weights as you exhale until the forearms are parallel to the floor and the whole arms are extended. Like many other arm exercises, only the forearm moves.. After a second contraction at the top, slowly lower the dumbbells back to their starting position as you inhale.. Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Janda Sit-Up
properties.description: Position your body on the floor in the basic sit-up position; knees to a ninety degree angle with feet flat on the floor and arms either crossed over your chest or to the sides. This will be your starting position.. As you strongly tighten your glutes and hamstrings, fill your lungs with air and in a slow (three to six second count) ascent, slowly exhale. Tip: It is important to tighten the glutes and hamstrings as this will cause the hip flexors to be inactivated in a process called reciprocal inhibition, which basically means that opposite muscles to the contracted ones will relax.. As you inhale, slowly go back in a controlled manner to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Janda Sit-Up
properties.description: Position your body on the floor in the basic sit-up position; knees to a ninety degree angle with feet flat on the floor and arms either crossed over your chest or to the sides. This will be your starting position.. As you strongly tighten your glutes and hamstrings, fill your lungs with air and in a slow (three to six second count) ascent, slowly exhale. Tip: It is important to tighten the glutes and hamstrings as this will cause the hip flexors to be inactivated in a process called reciprocal inhibition, which basically means that opposite muscles to the contracted ones will relax.. As you inhale, slowly go back in a controlled manner to the starting position.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Reverse Barbell Preacher Curls
properties.description: Grab an EZ-bar using a shoulder width and palms down (pronated) grip.. Now place the upper part of both arms on top of the preacher bench and have your arms extended. This will be your starting position.. As you exhale, use the biceps to curl the weight up until your biceps are fully contracted and the barbell is at shoulder height. Squeeze the biceps hard for a second at the contracted position.. As you breathe in, slowly lower the barbell until your upper arms are extended and the biceps is fully stretched.. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

properties.name: Reverse Barbell Preacher Curls
